<Author>jgeorge
<Content>Wonderful stay The Reforma marked the start of almost a month round trip to Mexico for my wife and I, and this proved to be an excellent start. We spent 3 nights here, giving us two full days to explore some of the city. If returning to Mexico we would certainly be very happy to use the Reforma again.We found all the staff, without exception, to be courteous and helpful at all times. Our suite was large and extremely comfortable. One drawback was the slightly noisy air-conditoning. The buffet breakfast was delicious, offering an extremely wide choice and very attractively presented. Unfortunately, we were in a room towards the back of the building, overlooking some construction work. (No noise though, whatsoever) It might be worth requesting a suite overlooking the main street .. the Reforma. We used the in-house restaurant, 'Evita's' on one night and enjoyed the meal very much, though thought it was a little on the pricey side.We used the small pool in the basement ... and had it all to ourselves. The laundry service was excellent.We chose the Reforma, partly through recommendations on this site, but also for it's location between the two main tourist attractions ... the Zocola area and Chapultepec ... for us, both were within walking distance (about 30 mins and 50 mins respectively). Both are well worth a visit, particularly the Templo Mayor, the Castillo and the Zoo (free entrance, but full of school parties when we were there). The tourist circular bus trip is well worthwhile.We used an 'authorised' taxi from the airport to the hotel, costing 240 peso and got the hotel to arrange a return taxi which cost 270 peso. Be very wary of flagging down taxis or using 'unauthorised' ones. I would not entertain driving in Mexico City! 
